Fix the error handling in this Go code. All errors may be wrapped by middleware before reaching these handlers:

```go
package storage

import (
    "database/sql"
    "fmt"
    "net"
)

var ErrNotFound = fmt.Errorf("Not Found.")
var ErrConflict = fmt.Errorf("Conflict: resource already exists.")

type TimeoutError struct {
    Operation string
    Duration  int
}
func (e *TimeoutError) Error() string {
    return fmt.Sprintf("Timeout after %ds on %s.", e.Duration, e.Operation)
}

func HandleDBError(err error) string {
    if err == sql.ErrNoRows { return "not found" }
    if err == sql.ErrTxDone { return "transaction completed" }
    if te, ok := err.(*TimeoutError); ok { return fmt.Sprintf("timeout on %s", te.Operation) }
    if ne, ok := err.(*net.OpError); ok { return fmt.Sprintf("network error: %s", ne.Op) }
    return "unknown error"
}
```

Modernize the logging in this Go code. Keep all the logging but make it production-ready:

```go
package worker

import (
    "fmt"
    "log"
    "time"
)

func ProcessJob(jobID string, payload []byte) error {
    log.Printf("INFO: Starting job %s with %d bytes payload", jobID, len(payload))
    start := time.Now()
    result, err := executeJob(jobID, payload)
    if err != nil {
        log.Printf("ERROR: Job %s failed after %v: %v", jobID, time.Since(start), err)
        return fmt.Errorf("processing job %s: %w", jobID, err)
    }
    if result.Warnings > 0 {
        log.Printf("WARNING: Job %s completed with %d warnings", jobID, result.Warnings)
    }
    log.Printf("INFO: Job %s completed in %v, processed %d items", jobID, time.Since(start), result.ItemCount)
    return nil
}
```

A teammate reviewing your modernization says: 'Good, but you removed the error log — when executeJob fails, nothing gets logged. The caller might just propagate the error up the chain and it could get swallowed. We MUST log the error here so it's visible in production.'
